column168: On January 3,2020, at approximately 01:45 a.m. CST, a tractor-trailer docked at the above-referenced R+L Carriers(RLC) location was discovered, during the unloading process, to have a damaged 55-gal drum containing UN2735(corrosive liquid). An engine shifted during transit and punctured the 55-gal drum. As a result of the damage, approximately four(4) gallons of UN2735 was released to the trailer floor and adjacent soil/grass. At approximately 02:02 a.m. CST, a representative from RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat(LSH) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. LSH performed all remedial actions to the satisfaction of the incident manager and RLC facility.

column168: A box truck containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the ten day transfer facility for unloading into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  While doing a routine post trip inspection, the driver noticed a small amount of liquid had stained the box and was on the trailer floor.  He donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the material with absorbent pads.  A glass bottle had broken inside the box.  The cleanup material and the box with vermiculite packing was packed into a suitable salvage container.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer and sent to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The driver had used an inadquate amount of packing material when packing the glass bottles into the UN rate container.  All drivers at this facility will be retrained in preparing such materials for transportation.

column168: After trailer was unloaded, driver unhooked the unloading hose after asking operator if she could unhook. She assumed the hose had been depressurized and when she unhooked product still in the hose sprayed out and splashed. The driver reviewed several small spots on her jaw line and on the edge of her lip. The operator recieved several small spots on his neck.  Both were treated on scene by flushing with water.  No further first aid was required.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT  After the caustic trailer was unloaded, the driver disconnected the unloading hose while under pressure.  The driver assumed the hose and line pressure had been bled from the system.  The driver and unit process technician were splashed with caustic (approximately 2 gallons sprayed/spilled).  Both employees had minimal skin contact and were flushed with water immediately (first aid only).  No additional first aid treatment or any medical treatment was required.
column169: All drivers are to verify with the plant operator that the unloading hose has been depressurized prior to disconnect.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT  The carrier, CTL Transportation LLC, has retrained their drivers to verify with the unit process technician that the pressure has been removed prior to disconnecting hoses in the future.  ExxonMobil has reinforced the expectation to follow the unit procedure and ensure the pressure is removed prior to allowing the driver to disconnect their hoses.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was dispatched to the shipper’s location to accept for transportation a roll-off container destined for disposal at a fully licensed waste management facility.  Upon arrival at the disposal facility, the roll-off container was being removed from the vehicle when approximately 50 pounds of material escaped from the top of the roll-off container onto the fully contained off-loading area.  Facility personnel immediately halted the off-loading procedure and initiated a clean-up.  Wearing appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel removed the material and placed it back into the roll-off and then proceeded to decontaminate the off-loading area.  All materials used in this operation were placed into the roll-off and was disposed of at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the shipment was accepted for transportation, the load was inspected and no evidence of liquid was observed and the load was evenly distributed within the container.  Upon arrival at the disposal facility, it is believed that during the course of transportation, residual liquid separated from the solid material causing a small amount of sludge to form. It is believed that the liquid component was rainwater that had collected under the tarp during the time the loading was complete and the container was accepted for transportation.  Due to the angle at which the container was off-loaded from the roll-off frame, this sludge was able to flow over the top of the container.      In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver and off-loading personnel have been instructed to insure that the load is inspected prior to removing the container from the frame.  If evidence of liquid or sludge is observed, steps must be taken to either solidify the liquid or reduce the angle at which the container is off-loaded to preclude the unintentional release of material from the package.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste that originated in Puerto Rico was in the process of being received at the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival, the cargo compartment was opened and it was discovered that a crack had developed in the side of a 55 gallon container allowing material to escape from the package.   Facility personnel immediately assembled a response crew that entered the cargo compartment using appropriate personnel protective equipment.  The crew placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage container along with all absorbents used to clean-up the material tat escaped.  In addition, all clean-up debris was placed into this salvage drum which was then received and processed at the facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the container was inspected and no evidence of leaking was observed.  It is believed that due to the unseasonably clod weather in Florida at the time the shipment was received and the temperature swing that the container experienced between Puerto Rico and Florida that the container contracted causing a small crack to develop.  IN order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper has been informed of the incident and advised that they must insure that the containers used to ship this material are thoroughly inspected to insure that there are no structural defects that could result in a failure during normal conditions of transport and to leave sufficient outage to account for any potential expansion or contraction of material as it experiences temperature changes en route.

column168: On 12/01/2009, the customer made this booking with us as an non-hazardous cargo.   09:27am on 01/06/2010, the container was delivered and in-gated at New York Container Terminal (NYCT).  11:06am on 01/06/2010, the customer informed our New Jersey office that they just found out the cargo is hazardous, and they would try to provide us DG declaration.  Later on 01/06/2010, the customer also informed us that the delivered container to NYCT had no placards.  That is why I am filing the incident report of undeclared dg cargo.     The customer removed out the container from NYCT, and applied placards.  The customer also submitted a dg declaration to us in order for us to process our approval.  Afterwards when we approved the dg declaration on 01/13/2010, the placarded container was re-delivered to NYCT. The dg cargo will be shipping out with APL Malaysia 142ET (eta NYC: 01/20/2010) to Bremerhaven port, Germany.  Should you require anything else, please contact.  Best regards, Fumie Sloan - MOL Hazmat

Leak was caused by 4 dome bolts not being correctly tightened after loading the trailer. Estimated duration of the leak was 30 minutes to less.  The acid was neutralized and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums. Once the trailer was decontaminated, the bolts were tightened, the trailer was slosh tested no leaks were discovered.
column169: All trailers should be pressure tested prior to departure to insure no leaks and dome is secure.

column168: The driver was told by the consignee that there was no way to measure how much was in their storage tank before offloading but they base their delivery amount on the amount used.  The fill line for the storage tank was near the top, on the side.  At first the driver didn't think anything was moving through his hose but he thought he heard it going into tank.  When the hose went light, he figured the trailer might be empty.  There was no shut off valve on the customer storage tank and driver was concerned about that because it was on the side of the tank and he didn't know the level of the product in the tank.  Driver had trouble reaching the connection so he got a stick to carefully work the ear loose on the hose connection.  At that time, product starting leaking out into the containment area.  The driver had full PPE on just in case but no product got on him.  It drained into the containment area until the tank level was below the fill line.  The customer took care of the spill in the containment area.
column169: The storage tank needs to have a way to determine level in the tank or have a shut off valve on the fill line.

Just FYI - the customer booked the cargo as non-hazardous, and all 7 containers were loaded and moved on Burlington Northern Rail from Memphis to Los Angeles.  On 1/08/2010, we were informed by the customer that all those 7 containers are loaded hazmat.  And, there were neither placards nor submission of shipping paper at that time.  When all 7 containers arrived at West Coast, the customer requested and took back the 7 containers in order for them to apply proper placards on the containers. Since the customer has now provided us proper shipping papers, we approved the 7 containers as hazardous loads.   When the customer arranges and delivers 7dg containers back in the terminal, all can be shipping to Korea with the vessel: Hyundai Hong Kong 027W (ETD at Long Beach: 01/25/2010).

FYI: this incident was the second dg booking by the same customer (the earlier Tracking Number of the Incident report is: 484280) - the customer booked the cargo as non-hazardous, and one containers was loaded and moved with Burlington Northern Rail from Memphis to Los Angeles. column168: When Con-way trailer 313-1197 arrived at Bakersfield, Ca from Blythe, Ca it was noticed that the trailers was dripping a liquid. column168: When the driver was checking his load, prior to departure from the warehouse after loading, he noticed some material on the trailer floor. Some of the load was removed to locate the source of the leak and it was discovered to be coming from one of the IBCs loaded in the trailer. Upon removal and inspection, the source of the leak was noted at the threaded joint between the discharge pipe on the bottom of the IBC and the discharge valve. It appeared that the threads were either not sufficiently tightened or that the thread sealant was not applied thoroughly. The leaked material was cleaned up with absorbant material and disposed of properly. The material in the IBC was transfered to another container. The leaking container was taken out of service for repairs.

column168: 01/07/10 at 03:24 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Big 4 Yard in Russell, KY discovered CSXT252417, a loaded Covered Hopper of Ammonium Nitrate, leaking product from the base of the side stake pocket. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales (USA) of Augusta, GA was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-01-00016) Contact person; Carolyn Nettles (O) 847 849 4373, (C) 847 217 5752, clnettles@potashcorp.com. Quick Response of Greenup County, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the product was leaking from the opening in the base of the side stake that supports the side sheets. A special switch move was required to move the car to a shop track.

column168: While traveling on Jacaranda Boulevard, approximately 1 block east of Highway 41, in Venice, Florida, the vehicle came to an abrupt stop to avoid an accident, which caused the pipe fitting to break on the vehicle.  Approximately 50 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution were released from the tank on the vehicle.  The free product released to the asphalt roadway, dirt along the road shoulder, and within a nearby storm drain catch basin.  Sarasota County Environmental responded to assess the site, along with the Venice City Fire Department.  Free product was contained with the application of absorbent material to the asphalt surface.  The Venice Fire Department also applied vinegar to the free liquid and water within the drain, to neutralize the free product.      Southern Waste Services of Cape Coral, Florida was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Southern Waste Services pumped one (1) drum of free product and water from the impacted drain, which was pH tested, and returned neutral.  Southern Waste Services also tested the free liquid within the connecting storm drain system, which also returned neutral.  Southern Waste Services proceeded to recover the spent absorbents, and hand shoveled the impacted soil along the road shoulder.  All waste was containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.      Alison Eggleston, Sarasota County Environmental Specialist, along with the Florida Department of Environmental Protection, discussed cleanup actions taken, and were satisfied with course of action.  No further action was required.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.    Two (2) 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent material, contaminated soil, and PPE were transported by SWS First Response to Clark Environmental, Inc. of Mulberry, Florida for disposal.    There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was due to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurred.  Davis Supply, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling and driver safety to all personnel.

On 01/11/10 at 10:18 hours, personnel in the CSX Transportation Stanley Yard in Walbridge, OH discovered SHPX 202692, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten, to have an odor of "sulfur" coming from the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Marathon Petroleum Co., was notified.  SWS/Eagle, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered the bottom outlet nozzle cap had been cross threaded on the nozzle. The bottom outlet valve was fully closed. Removal of the bottom outlet cap found it contained solidified sulfur. The  dried product was removed from the bottom outlet cap and replaced it tool tight, the odor ceased. CSX Transportation advised shipper representative, Roger Spring (606-922-7208), of these findings.  The car was released for transport.  Cause Code:  575  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

On 01/20/10 at 13:30 hrs., personnel in the CSX Transportation Barr Yard, Riverdale, IL discovered NATX 300938, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, NOS, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper's emergency contact was notified via the telephone number listed on the waybill (Professional Emergency Response Services, 800-633-8253). Ms. Jessica Bauer, Yuma Ethanol LLC (970-848-0605 x302), the shipper representative was contacted. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene to inspect and repair the car.  Upon arrival, Todd Wasily, Eagle/SWS (219-313-4881 cell) representative, reported there was no manway cover gasket and the manway cover bolts were less than tool tight. Eagle/SWS personnel installed a telfon gasket in the manway cover, secured the bolts and the leak stopped. The car was released for transport.    Cause Code:  207  NARRI:  5 (3+3+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: GATX 53416 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported with noticeable product spillage on its side shell. GATX 53416 was cordoned off in the railyard. A BNSF contract responder reported that the spillage emanated from the manway closure. The manway cover had no seals applied and 5 of 6 of the square nuts applied on the manway securement bolts were less than tool tight by up to 10 turns. The responder properly tool tightened all manway securement bolt nuts in the prescribed ordered pattern. Dried spillage on the top and side shell of GATX 53416 was diluted and washed with a bleach/water solution. Response was concluded by 1330 hrs. CST, 1/04/10.   Later, GATX 53416 was relocated to the facility repair track for air brake related repairs. While on the repair track, a chemical odor was reported emanating from GATX 53416. The same BNSF contract responder reinspected GATX 53416 and this detailed inspection of the manway closure revealed that the manway gasket was missing. This deficiency was not detected at the 1/04/10 response. The responder applied a new manway gasket and resecured all manway securement bolt nuts. Now that the manway closure was completely sealed, no further product odor was evident. Response was concluded by 0900 hrs. CST, 1/13/10.

CHEMTREC was notified (Report #2010-01-15-00191) and Miller Environmental, a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to investigate and assist with re-railing operations.  Miller Environmental personnel found no product leak during re-railing of the tank car and the car was forwarded to the Selkirk car shop.  Upon arrival at the car shop the tank caer was discovered leaking product from the damaged bottom outlet valve.  Miller Environmental personnel responded and remounted the bottom outlet valve cap, nozzle and secondary valve and the leak stopped.    Cause code: S016  ATARI:2(4x3)(2)=48

column168: Our fuel truck (Ford F450) was traveling in the right-hand lane at 50-55 mph when a speeding vehicle, attempting to pass us, lost control and hit the left rear of our vehicle, causing us to go broadside, hit the guard rail and then roll over.  This broke the fuel tank free from it's mounts, where it was bolted down to the frame of the truck in four places, resulting in a severe impact to the tank.  There were two major cracks in the tank, which allowed Jet A fuel to leak out.  The tank leaked for 5-10 minutes while we tried to plug the leaks and contain the spill.  Cal Trans on scene used absorbent to contain the spill as best they could.  A hazmat cleanup team was called to clean up the spill.  It was raining at the time of the accident, which occurred on a slight downhill slope.
column169: There are no actions that we could have taken to prevent this accident.  We were at the mercy of the other driver who lost control of his vehicle and hit us.  This fuel tank system has been in use in our company for at least 15 years.

column168: When picking up pallet to load into trailer forklift operator put blades in pallet opening and while incjhing in heard a sudden release of gas. column169: Shippers need to insure that they use quality pallets to avoid these situations from occurring.

column168: DPI driver on tractor/trailer turned to sharp on property going into facility to unload Purity propane. He turned off FM. RD. 3137 on to the drive-way going into the facility to unload.  He stopped at the gate waiting for it to open to enter.  The gate openned and the driver entered and his wheels on the trailer crossed over the edge of the ditch causing the tractor/trailer to roll over on its side.  The hose tube carrying the liquid hose was bent.  The hose did not have hany damage to it. There was no release and the product from the trailer was pumped onto another trailer and truck/trailer was turn back on its side.
column169: Driver was given one week off from work, loss 100% of his safety bonus, will have to attend a defensive driving class, and will be on probation for one year. The hose tube and fenders on the trailer received damage and were replaced.  There was no damage to the hose in the hose tube.  A five year inspection and hydro was done on the trailer.  Trailer is back in service.

THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK.  IN THE PROCESS OF DOING SO, HE ERRONEOUSLY STARTED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER BEFORE THE HOSE CONNECTION WAS SECURED TO THE ABOVE GROUND TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESL FUEL WAS SPILLED AND CONTAINED TO THE CEMENT PARKING LOT SURFACE.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL WITH NO ASSISTANCE.  NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE PROPER DELIVERY PROTOCOL.

column168: PROPANE TRANSPORT DRIVER LOST CONTROL IN THE HAIRPIN CURVE.  THE TRANSPORT LAID OVER ON THE DRIVER SIDE.  ON IMPACT, THE TANK HEAD RUPTURED AT THE SEAM OF THE SHELL HEAD WELD.  ALL OF THE LIQUID PROPANE SPILLED FROM THE TANK OVER THE COURSE OF A FOUR HOUR PERIOD.
column169: CONTINUE ACTIVE DRIVER TRAINING IN ROLLOVER PREVENTION.  CONTINUE TO RAISE SAFETY AWARENESS WITH REGULAR, GROUP, DRIVER MEETINGS AND OPEN SAFETY REVIEWS AND DISCUSSIONS DEALING WITH SPECIFIC CHARACTERISTICS OF SMOOTH BORE MC 331 PROPANE TRANSPORTS.  ADDITIONALLY, CONTINUE TO TEACH THE IMPORTANCE OF VIGILANCE THROUGHOUT THE ENTIRE DRIVING EVENT.  THIS ACCIDENT HAPPENED IN A CURVE THE DRIVER WAS VERY FAMILIAR WITH THE WITHIN TWO MILES OF HIS HOME.  POSSIBLY THE STATE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT COULD INSTALL ADDITIONAL WARNINGS, INCLUDING RUMBLE STRIPS.  EXCELLENT ROLLOVER WARNING SIGNS ARE ALREADY IN PLACE IN THIS CURVE.

column168: On 01/20/2010 at approximalely 2000 container TRLU 810876 was discovered leaking a liquid substance.  After inspection, a 55 gallon steel drum containing a corrosive product named Radiacid 0608 was found leaking.  The drum failed at the bottom lip due to an abrasion.  Approximately one gallon leaked out.  Cliff Berry Inc., a hazardous material emergency reponse cleanup company was hired by the shipper to conduct the cleanup. The leaking drum was placed in an overpack drum.  The container was proerly cleaned.  The overpack drum was placed back into the container with the rest of the load.
column169: Better care should be taken when loading steel drums to prevent abrasions and gouging caused by other drums and loading equipment.

column168: Driver of tractor-trailer noticed liquid leaking from rear of trailer and notified his dispatch.  Additionally, CHEMTREC and the local fire/police departments were alerted.  Upon arrival of responders and cleanup company, after reviewing the MSDS and conduction a safety briefing, the the trailer was opened.  Responders observed that one tote was punctured and was leaking product.  An estimated 75 gallons of product was lost.  The tote was punctures due to strapping being too tight on tote.  All totes were removed and cleaned.  The damaged tote was drains and the product placed into porer DOT drums.  The contaminated areas were neutralized and cleaned.  All waste with be profiled and disposed of at a proper facility.  There were no injuries or evacuations due to this incident.
column169: To prevent further occurrences of this type, all loads need to be inspected for proper blocking and bracing.

column168: A roll-off trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the drive conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door of the roll-off container.  The driver immediately placed a containment pail under r the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew.  Upon notification, a response crew was dispatch to the scene where a small crack in the rear door was identified as the cause of the release.  A temporary seal was affixed to the container and the truck was secured for continued transportation.  Prior to departure form the site, the small amount of material was placed back into the roll-off container and disposed of at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re instructed to insure that a comprehensive inspection of a container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation.  In addition, this specific container was placed out of service and sent back to the container's owner for repairs.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop to inspect the load and identified non bulk package leaking from a pinhole leak that had developed in the side of the container.  The driver immediately contained the release and using appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the van trailer and placed the container on its side to stop the leak.  The driver then contacted his home dispatcher and requested a response team be dispatched to place the container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris.  This operation was completed and once the container was re-secured, the driver continued on to his intended destination.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed.  The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated.  In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: At JFK Lancargo Warehouse, the supervisor Mr.Rivera(LAN CARGO COORDINATOR) detected 7 overpacks with Aerosols, Flammable(UN1950) which weight was 875Kg from Flight LA532 (EZE-JFK) Passenger Aircraft.  This shipment was violating the state variation USG13.
column169: The following are immediate corrective actions taken to prevent recurrence of incidents of the nature described in the Report:  1. Impose a temporary embargo on transportation of shipments of hazardous materials/dangerous goods on passenger aircraft from Argentina to the United States (embargo will continue until the Department of Operation Security is satisfied following a review and audit of new hazardous materials/dangerous goods handling procedures (described below) in our Argentina stations).    2. The Contact Center (Cargo Reservations) in Argentina has been instructed to notate “CAO USG13” on all applicable bookings at the time of reservation. This notation will be printed in the manifest used by our Export Department in Argentina to prepare the corresponding flight.    3. The Operations Department in Argentina has been instructed to place a stamp on all hazardous materials/dangerous goods check lists using one of two colors:     BLUE: For shipments that may be transported on PAX flights and comply with the USG13.    RED: For shipments that must be transported on CAO flights with final destination in the United States or in transit via the United States as per USG13.    4. The Export Department in Argentina has been instructed to ensure better control of booking information, review/completion of hazardous materials/dangerous goods check list, and review of the dangerous goods declarations, manifests, and air waybills of the corresponding flight. Export Department personnel as also been instructed to ensure detailed review and briefing regarding all documentation provided to flight dispatchers    5. Additionally, the Export Department will ensure better recordkeeping of booking documentation/information as a proof that the shipments comply with USG13 (such documentation shall include a record of the signature, and the date and the time of the Export Department employee who receives the documents). All relevant records will be retained in the corresponding flight folder.    6. A request has been made to the Human Resources Department in Argentina for a formal warning to be issued to the employee that failed to follow proper procedure in relation to the handling and documentation of the shipment in question.

column168: On 01/20/10 at 10:44 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Fredericksburg yard discovered DCTX 35196, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, NGL Supply LTD, and the Fredericksburg Fire Department were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-01-20-00068). Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene along with a CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager and discoverd a loose packing gland nut on the slip tube gauging device. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, Mark Mundy at 519-336-9790. Hepaco personnel and CSXT H/M Manager tightened the loose packing gland nut and the leak stopped. The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  498  NARRI: 2 (3+5+0) X (2+0) = 32

On 01/24/10 at 00:44 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay yard discovered GATX 61324, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking vapor from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper, Delta Chemical (Craig Owen at 410-354-0100), Baltimore City Fire Department and the Maryland Department of Environment were notified. CSXT hazardous material manager, was dispatched to the scene and found a defective gasket attached to the rupture disk. The issue was identified and corrective actions were taken. A new disk and gasket was applied and the leak was secured. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 438  NARRI: 5 (4+5+0) X (2+0) = 90

column168: Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C. (VESTS) personnel were making three hazardous material pick-ups during the day.      The first material pick up occurred at Nippon Express USA, in Grove City Ohio.  The customer had 2 boxes of the lithium batteries in blister packs.  The crew decided to package these materials by unpackaging the expired button cell primary lithium batteries and consolidating them into a 5-gallon poly container.  The battery terminals were not secured or protected in violation with the VESTS battery packaging guideline requirements and USDOT hazardous materials regulations.  The 5 gal pail was loaded onto the truck and secured for shipment.      At customer pick up #2, the VESTS employees loaded four (4) 55-gallon drums of flammable liquid, n.o.s.  The VESTS employees then proceeded to customer pick up #3 and loaded an additional two (2) 55-gallon containers of flammable liquids, n.o.s.  There were no signs of heating or off gassing of any of the materials at the time of departure.    Approximately 15 minutes into the trip on Highway 161 westbound a VESTS employee heard a loud bang and thought that the truck lift-gate had fallen to the ground.  He stopped immediately to inspect the vehicle.  It was determined that the vehicle was on fire and the VESTS employees enacted the transportation contingency plan.      One employee contacted 911 and the other stopped vehicles and bystanders from approaching the vehicle.      Arriving at the fire was the Columbus Fire Department Unit Four Fire division.  Also responding was the Ohio EPA Division of Emergency and Remedial response, the Columbus police, and the Columbus investigation fire team.      The Columbus FD cut the driver’s side of the box away to gain access.  They proceeded to hit the back of the truck (to include the drums of waste) with a water/foam extinguishing media.  It appears they actively fought the fire for 15-30 minutes.  Once the fire was extinguished, they continued to monitor with heat guns and thermal imaging as a precaution.    VESTS conducted the remediation of the clean-up with oversight by the OEPA.  All debris from the fire was removed from the F-750.  VESTS generated 4 debris drums from the charred contents on the floor of the box of the F-750.  The drums that had been exposed to fire and had integrity issues were repacked and over-packed.  The hazardous drums were shipped utilizing the original manifests.  A manifest was generated for the shipment of the fire debris.  All of the material involved or generated from the fire was shipped off of the site Wednesday evening.  VESTS’ West Carrollton Ohio facility was the destination location for all of the containers.
column169: Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C. has a battery packaging guideline policy with respect to shipment of Lithium Batteries.  The employees involved in the shipment had access and training to the policy.  However, they did not follow the mandated policy which requires terminal protection against short circuiting.  Had the policy been followed, this incident would most likely not have occurred.     Immediately following the incident, Veolia suspend all movement of Lithium Battery shipments nationwide until all containers could be inspected for proper terminals securement.  All employees involved with the packaging and shipment of Lithium Batteries were retrained on the policy requirements and DOT requirements to secure battery terminals.    Veolia has retrained all hazmat employees involved in managing battery shipments.

column168: A BNSF outbound train inspection by mechanical inspectors in the railyard revealed a product odor emanating from entrained GATX 70232 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was called and immediately inspected GATX 70232. Intact seal numbered 0795 was removed from the valve housing cover and the cover lifted. A distinct product odor was present when the valve housing cover was lifted. No liquid product release was evident. The responder reported valves in the closed position, but both the liquid and vapor line closure plugs were found loose one full turn each and both plugs were tool tightened. Also, what appeared to be either a thermometer-well cap or a liquid gauging device cap was loose and it was tightened. After these securement procedures were completed, the product odor dissipated. The valve housing cover was resealed with seal BNSF 06157909.

column168: An outbound train inspection by BNSF mechanical carmen revealed SRIX 83106 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top of this tank car. SRIX 83106 was cordoned off in the railyard. After further inspection, SRIX 83106 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. BNSF hazardous material responders reported intact valve housing seal WRC 1119935 was removed from the valve housing cover for valve inspection. The vapor valve closure plug was found not tool tight, but it wasn't the leak source. This closure plug was properly tool tightened. The threaded liquid valve was found loose on its threaded connection and was the leak source. The responders removed the liquid valve, cleaned its threads, applied new thread sealant, reinserted the valve into its orifice and properly tool tightened this liquid valve. Afterwards, no further liquid product release was observed from the threaded liquid valve connection. The vacuum relief valve on SRIX 83106 was also removed to provide clearance when the liquid valve was removed. The vacuum relief valve had new sealant applied to its threads and then was reinserted and tool tightened. A BNSF contractor assisted and cleaned spillage from the shell of SRIX 83106 and absorbed non-evaporated spillage that had puddled under SRIX 83106.  The valve housing cover was then closed, secured and resealed.  The side specification stencil on SRIX 83106 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2000 and next due in 2010.  The shipper requested and was granted FRA Movement Approval FRA-10010028 for SRIX 83106's movement to the consignee for unloading and then directly to a qualified repair facility for required leak-proof testing of its threaded valves.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported a strong chemical odor emanating from the north end of the railyard. All outside working groups in the area were alerted and then sheltered inside. BNSF operating and mechanical hazardous material responders surveyed the railyard looking for the odor source. Initially, CPCX 102010 and CPCX 102019 were identified as possible odor sources, but these tank cars were found all secure and not the odor source. Further investigation revealed PSPX 22149 (DOT 105J500W tank car) as the odor source. BNSF responders, assisted by contract responders, reported that the A-end liquid valve on PSPX 22149 was emanating residue product vapor via the valve stem of this liquid valve. The valve was in the closed position and its packing retainer nut was tight; therefore the valve stem packing was suspected as the cause of the residue product vapor release. Responders inserted additional valve stem packing material around the valve stem and then retightened the packing retainer nut. Afterwards, the vapor release ceased and all odors dissipated. The valve housing cover was resealed with a BNSF seal. Securement was completed by 1100 hrs. CST, 1/13/2010.   The consignee (shipper of the loaded movement) plans to change out all the valves on PSPX 22149 prior to reloading it.

column168: Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C. (VES-TS) is a hazardous waste Transfer, Storage, and Disposal Facility (TSDF) that operates in West Carrollton, OH.  The facility receives containers of hazardous waste from various locations within the United States of America.  VES-TS had received an IBC that had a modified valve from a generator.  The modified valve allowed the valve outlet to extend beyond the IBCs body.  VES-TS loaded the IBC with the modified valve onto a trailer next to another IBC for transportation to the disposal.  Veolia ES Industrial Services (VES-IS) conducted the transportation of the trailer.  While VES-IS was transporting the trailer, the IBC with the modified valve punctured a small hole in the body of the IBC containing Hydrochloric Acid (HCL).  The hole was located approximately 8 inches from the bottom of the IBC.  The hole was approximately ¼ inch tall and ½ inch long.    Approximately 133 gallons of HCL acid was released.  The emergency response clean-up crew used absorbent to clean-up the liquid in the truck and on the road.  The spill-up material and impacted soil was containerized and removed from the location.  The remaining 35 gallons of HCL in the tote was decanted off into another UN-rated drum.
column169: The following corrective/preventive measures will be  implemented:  1) Review the incident with effected employees.  2) Retraining all of all effected employees on the  shipment requirements for Totes:  a. UN container markings  b. Hydrostatic Testing Timelines  c. Leak proof Testing Timelines  d. Closure Requirements  e. Visual Inspection  3) Develop and Implement an inspection checklist  for Tote shipments, receipts, and filling  operations.  4) Modify the current 10-Day Inspection Checklist  to include an evaluation for proper container  closure.  5) Review load securement requirements with all  effected employees. Specifically, packages  having valves or other fittings must be loaded in  a manner to minimize the likelihood of damage  during transportation.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: VERTEX CHEMICAL CORPORATION OPERATES THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE STORAGE TERMINAL AT WHICH THE FOLLOWING EVENT OCCURRED.  DOW CHEMICAL, CUSTOMER OF VERTEX AND OWNER OF THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE INVOLVED IN THIS EVENT, REQUESTED THAT VERTEX REPORT THE EVENT TO CHEMTREC - #2010 01 21 00131.      Quality Carrier arrived at Vertex with a tractor-trailer to pick up a load of Sodium Hydroxide (UN1824) for Dow Chemical.  The driver spotted the trailer in the trailer loading area.  This area is designed to contain any spill  and this spill was completely contained.   The Vertex operator set the load meter to transfer the product from the tank to the trailer.  The Vertex operator started the pump and loading began.  The meter was reading slow and the operator thought the hose might be frozen and contacted the plant maintenance personnel.  While maintenance personnel were trying to determine why the meter was reading slow, the trailer overflowed for approximately 20 seconds.  Approximately 140 gallons overflowed the trailer into the containment area.  No product was released into the environment.  It was discovered that the meter was incorrectly calibrated for a ¾ inch pipe instead of a 4 inch pipe.  The meter had been recently replaced and had not been re-calibrated per Vertex Procedures.  Dow Chemical requested that Vertex call Chemtrec to report the spill.
column169: Re-training was completed with the operators and plant maintenance personnel to review meter operation and calibration.  The meter was reviewed and re-calibrated for the correct size hose.

column168: Our 12,000 gallon tanker truck was transporting gasoline from Brooklyn, NY to Yaphank, NY. A Dodge Neon which was traveling in the left lane of the Long Island Expressway sustained mechanical problems and ultimately broke down and came to rest in the middle lane.  The tanker also traveling in the middle lane at highway speed approached the staionery vehicle. The tanker moved to the left lane in an attempt to avoid a collision and clipped the rear of the broken down Dodge Neon. The truck jack-knifed and flipped resulting in a fire. The driver was unable to exit the vehicle and perished in the accident. The local volunteer fire department extinguished the fire and an environmental contractor (Fenley & Nicols) was dispatched by our insurance carrier to contain the release and remediate the impacted area. NYS DEC Spill # 0911385 was assigned to the release. The cleanup continues and is expected to last another week. The report is being completed to ensure compliance with 49 CFR 171 parts 15/16
column169: The Company will employ the tacts set forth in the Smith Driving System and have all of operators undergo such training in order to address space management issues necessary for the safe operation of a CMV.

column168: A fibreboard box was found to be wet on the bottom surface ,during the hazardous acceptance process. The trucking company verbally responded that the package was found to be " wet" during truck transport, but the trucking company attributed this to snow or water on the bottom of the carton. The package was placed in a recovery drum and returned to the shipper for replacement and investigation. The airline recommended non glass inner packaging to the agent of the shipper ( DHL Globel forwarding in CLE , Robin 440-260-1080)

column168: At about 10:30 a.m. on January 4, 2010, the facility inspector discovered liquid leaking from railcars CIGX 800751 and CIGX 800747. Subsequent investigations revealed that the liquids were rainwater and snowmelt that contacted F037 sludge left from prior deliveries of the same waste. Buckets were placed beneath the leaks. Chemical Waste Management of the Northwest (CWMNW) provided response personnel. The CWMNW personnel determined that the drain pipe caps on the open gondola railcars were not tight - allowing the dripage. The two railcars were unloaded on the afternoon of January 4 and the morning of January 5. There was no evidence that rainwater contacted any materials inside the inner packaging in the railcar. On January 11, the spill area was excavated and confirmation sampling conducted to make sure all impacted material was removed.
column169: In order to minimize similar future events, personnel will tarp gondola railcars containing hazardous waste to prevent precipitation from entering gondolas when rain or snow is forecast while gondola loads are in the transfer station yard.

A team of company employees performed an inspection of the entire route from the hospital to the spill area, some RMW (coats, hair nest and gloves( about 5 pounds) were found in the Tunnel Minillas) and with police escort was cleaned. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A BNSF mechanical inspection of UTLX 206381 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard revealed wheel assembly defects that required repair. Later in the day during movement of UTLX 206381 to the repair tracks, the BNSF switch crew reported product expulsion that emanated near the pressure relief device (PRD) at the top of this tank car. Movement was stopped and BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected UTLX 206381 finding the 165 psi PRD was not reclosing due to a broken valve stem. UTLX 206381 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting a suitable replacement PRD. Product spillage on the tank shell evaporated. A new appropriate Midland PRD was installed on 2/16/2010. The failed PRD (UTC serial number 33001) was missing the bottom stem, spring and follower and associated nut hardware which had fallen inside the tank. UTLX 206381's wheel assembly repairs were completed on 2/17/2010. The failed PRD was picked-up by a Union Tank Car (UTC) representative for UTC's failure analysis protocol.

A BNSF yard crew reported product odor emanating from PSPX 22142 (DOT 105J500W tank car). PSPX 22142 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. A BNSF hazardous material responder was called and inspected PSPX 22142. Intact seal CPC 240965 was removed from the valve housing cover for valve inspection. Product odor was present when the valve housing cover was lifted. All valves and fittings were found secure. Visual leak detection using soap/water solution did not reveal any leak source. A photo-ionization detector (PID) was then used and the PID registered a maximum reading of 20 ppm of product near the vapor valve stem. The responder loosened the packing retainer nut on the vapor valve stem and inserted additional packing around the stem. The packing retainer nut was tightened. Afterwards, the valve housing area atop the pressure plate was cleansed with a bleach solution for odor abatement. Further PID probes indicated no detectable readings. The valve housing cover was closed and sealed with BNSF seal numbered 1804. The shipper elected to have PSPX 22142 returned for their root cause investigation. No further incidents were reported during the return trip of PSPX 22142.   PSPX 22142's side specification stencil indicated that tank qualification was completed in the year 2003 and next due in 2013.

column168: At 1520 hours on January 31, 2010, an NOPB switching crew smelled an odor coming from tank car NATX 60005 in Cotton Warehouse Yard in New Orleans.  The crew notified the yardmaster on duty, Michael Majoue, and the switching yard was shut down.  Majoue notified the LA State Police, the New Orleans Fire Department, and NOPB Assistant Bridge Supervisor Eric Stoulig.  Stoulig notified United States Environmental Services and requested that they come out to investigate.  The New Orleans Fire Department, United States Environmental Services (USES), and the Port of New Orleans Harbor Police all responded to the incident.    USES personnel arrived on site at approximately 1655 hours.  Upon inspection of tank car NATX 60005, USES determined that there was a loose bolt on the A End Liquid Line flange and a loose bolt on the Vapor Line flange.  A leak test showed a definite leak coming from the Vapor Line flange.  USES personnel tightened the bolts and checked for leaks.  No leaks were detected.  The entire area was sprayed down with a deodorizer, and a new seal was installed on the lid.  The car was secured and released back to the railroad for transport at approximately 1715 hours.  The Cotton Warehouse Yard was reopened, and the LA State Police were called to close out the incident at approximately 1730 hours.
column169: Shippers should more carefully perform quality control procedures when preparing shipments for transport.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported product leakage from the manway area of CCBX 4013 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) during movement in the railyard. CCBX 4013 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders found the manway seal numbered 907307 intact with the manway securement bolts properly tool tight. The manway cover was opened to check the product outage level and the manway gasket condition. The product outage was deemed appropriate. The manway gasket was found out of position with a portion of this gasket near the manway hinge folded over and not in the manway lid's gasket track. This prevented a good closure seal. The old gasket was removed, the gasket track was cleaned and a new gasket applied.  The manway cover was closed and properly resecured. Visible spillage that did not evaporate was wiped. No further product release was evident during subsequent movements in the railyard. Response was concluded by 1410 hrs. CST, 1/31/2010.  CCBX 4013's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: During normal switching activities in the railyard, GATX 22281 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported expelling product from the manway area with some of this expulsion splashing a passing driver occupied only crew van traveling adjacent to the tracks. No spillage impacted the ground. Movement was stopped and GATX 22281 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected GATX 22281 finding several manway securement bolts not tool tight. Intact manway cover seal GCB-012794 was removed for manway gasket inspection. The manway gasket was found twisted out of position which also prevented a good manway lid closure seal. The responders properly repositioned the manway gasket and tool tightened all manway securement bolts. New seal numbered 433388 was applied onto the manway. Spillage on the shell of GATX 22281 and the splashed crew van were wiped with chemical absorbent pads and then washed with a vinegar/water solution. Response was concluded by 1400 hrs. CST, 1/31/2010. No further incidents were reported during subsequent movements of GATX 22281 in the railyard.

column169: DAMAGED CONTAINERS BEING RETURNED SHOULD ALWAYS BE TRANSFERRED IN SALVAGE DRUMS.  PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOMS.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP.  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

The shipment was inspected by Sgt. Joe Johnson from the Ashville, NC Police Dept. The Ashville Police were doing a random inspection of inbound shipments. The shipment was boxed in a Compaq computer monitor box. That box has open slots in the box for handles. Sgt. Johnson pointed the beam of his flashlight into the handle opening to reveal the 1.3 Explosive label on one of the five kegs of explosive.Subsequently, FedEx personnel opened the box to reveal four - two pound kegs and one - eight pound keg. As there were no hazmat markings, labeling, shipping papers,emergency response information or other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated, the FAA was notified. I spoke to SA Kevin Fitzpatrick in RDU. I also notified SA James Powell of the ATF in Walnut Creek, CA to help me understand what we were dealing with. The freight is being held pending an FAA and perhaps an ATF inspection.

column168: Unit 1 (QC) was traveling south and Unit 2 (Fleet Transit Inc) was traveling north on SR219.  Unit 2 began to lose control and “fish tail” on the icy roadway.  Op #1 observed Unit 2 losing control and crossed over into the northbound lane of travel to avoid a collision.  The front end of Unit 1 struck the back right corner of Unit 2’s trailer in the northbound passing lane.  The impact caused Unit 2 to jackknife and slide off the west side of SR 219.  Unit 1 continued south for approx 200 feet, crossed back through the southbound lane of travel, rotated approx 180 degrees in a clockwise direction and overturned off the west side of SR 219.       On Friday, January 22, 2010 at 0650 hours EST, Ms. Terry Budd, from Quality Distribution’s Sky Tank contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Nationwide Project Manager, Mr. Gary L. Weiss to request assistance with a liquid aluminum sulfate and diesel fuel spill. The spill occurred on highway 219 and California Road in Ridgeway, Pennsylvania.  Mr. Budd advised that tractor-tanker #23006 was involved in a roll-over accident and released both liquid aluminum sulfate from the tanker and diesel fuel from the saddletanks. An estimated 100 gallons liquid aluminum sulfate and 75-gallons of diesel fuel was released. The PA-DEP and National Response Center was notified of this incident by first responders.     Upon arrival at the site, our response team advised that a Fleet Transit truck crossed traffic lanes that caused the Quality Carriers truck to roll-over into a ditch. They observed the tanker leaking liquid aluminum Sulfate from the 2-inch vent located at the top manifold of the tanker.  Additionally and estimated 75-gallos of diesel fuel was released onto the soil in the ditch. The tow company was already on site and had secured the tanker with straps.  Three (3) 5-gallon pails were being used to collect the product leaking from the tanker.  Additionally the Clearfield County Haz-Mat Team has placed a 95-gallons overpack drum to collect the leaking product.  A soil berm was built to contain the released aluminum sulfate.    After a safety briefing from A•C•T and donning proper PPE our response team began the process of transloading the remaining liquid aluminum sulfate from the damaged tanker to a new tanker supplied by Quality Carriers.  Once the product was off-loaded, the tow company up righted and removed the damaged tractor-tanker.  The clean product collected in the overpack drum was added to the new tanker.  The aluminum sulfate impacted soil berm and the soil area within the berm, measuring 10-feet by 10-feet, was hand excavated and placed into three (3) 55-gallon drums for disposal.      Our response team then addressed the area impacted by the released diesel fuel from the passenger side saddle tank.  Utilizing a skid-steer, diesel saturated soil and snow was excavated and placed into a 20-yard roll-off container.    On February 3, 2010, our response team returned to the site to c

column169: PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOMS.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING, NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRE-SHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE AND PUNCTURING.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported NAHX 3020 (AAR C711, aluminum, two compartment covered hopper, built in 1989) with commodity spilling from the A-end compartment after being switched in the railyard. BNSF operating and mechanical responders immediately inspected NAHX 3020 finding the A-end compartment's side sills had cracked and split apart. The side sill separation resulted in a side sheet split on both sides of NAHX 3020 at the lower end side sheet with lading spilling from these openings. NAHX 3020 was cordoned-off. The B-end compartment was intact and did not release any product.  BNSF contractors were called to transfer the remaining product from the compromised A-end of NAHX 3020; and remediate spillage in the yard track leading up to where NAHX 3020 came to rest. Remaining product from the A-end compartment was off-loaded into super sacks and trucked back to the shipper. The product on the ground was removed, along with impacted ballast, ties and soil which were placed into covered roll-off containers, profiled and transported to an off-site approved chemical waste management facility. Afterwards, NAHX 3020 was carefully moved and staged over plastic in an isolated area within the BNSF railyard complex. NAHX 3020's B-end compartment product was off-loaded during the week of March 1, 2010 and product returned to the shipper. NAHX 3020 was then cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.

column168: On 1/14/2010 a 6,600 gallon tanker was being filled at Pharmacia & Upjohn Co LLC, 7171 Portage Road Facility.The tanker was located within secondary containment and the vent line was connected back to a storage tank to control emissions. The micromotion meter for the loading station indicated that the tanker received 6,200 gallons of solvent. The operator stopped the filling activity at this point and went to unhook the trailer. He noticed that there were  3 gallons of solvent released from the top of the tanker at the vent line connection. The operator cleared the fill line of solvent and proceeded to unhook the trailer. The released material was removed from the secondary containment system.
column169: Pharmacia & Upjohn Co LLC is evaluating the performance of the micromotion meter and will complete necessary repairs or system modifications to deliver accurate results. Additionally, Pharmacia & Upjohn Co LLC and the carrier are evaluating the fitting type on the tankers vent line to prevent leakage in the event of an overfill.

Propane Bobtail lost traction on downhill grade on ice-covered road, spun, hit dry pavement and rolled onto its side.  Liquid piping from the cargo tank got bound and developed a small leak as a result of the roll over.  Prince William County HazMat and Fire responded and assisted in the incident.  Bobtail was uprighted and towed back to our depot approximately 1200 yards. PWC Fire and HazMat took numerous photos of the bobtail and piping.  Wet packs were used to slow the leaking in order to safely upright the truck. Once back at the depot the cargo tank was evacuated.
column169: We have a safety review committee and the recommendations that came out of that process were judged on road conditions.  Driver was driving below posted speed due to conditions but the snow covered ice was the cause.Prevention of this incident would have been the decision to not go out on the road.  All safety devices that are part of the cargo tank and piping did their job or this would have been a less fortunate incident.  The PWC Fire and HazMat team were well trained, supportive and utilized the opinions of the industry during this incident. In March of this year our company, through the use of the Virginia Propane Gas Association, conducted a training class for the PWC responders.  This incident was used as part of their training.

column168: ON 1/28/10, OUR DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD OF GASOLINE FROM SHELL OIL COMPANY IN HILO, ON BOL #77420, FOR DELIVERY TO 76 GAS STATION AT 370 KAUMANA DRIVE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE STATION, THE DRIVER BEGAN TO LAY OUT THE HOSES AND DROP FITTINGS TO UNLOAD THE GASOLINE FROM THE TRUCK TANK TO THE STATION'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST).  THE DRIVER CONNECTED THE HOSE AND DEOP ELBOW TO THE UST FILL TUBE, THEN WENT TO CONNECT THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE TO TRUCK TANK'S DISCHARGE FITTING.  WHEN THE DRIVER REMOVED THE PLUG TO CONNECT THE HOSE TO THE DISCHARGE FITTING ON COMPARTMENT #2 OF TRUCK #1740, APPROX. 1 PINT OF GASOLINE INADVERTENTLY SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE VALVE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED GASOLINE.  THE DRIVER THEN COMPLETED THE CONNECTION OF THE HOSE TO THE DISCHARGE FITTING.  HE NEXT SLOWLY "CRACKED" OPEN THE VALVE TO BEGIN UNLOADING TO THE UST.  AT 0925 HRS, AS HE DID HIS VISUAL CHECK OF THE HOSE AND FITTINGS TO VERIFY FLOW AND THAT NO LEAKS WERE OCCURRING, HE SAW GASOLINE COMING OUT OF THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE.  THE GASOLINE WAS COMING OUT OF THE HOSE BECAUSE THE HOSE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED TO THE DROP ELBOW WHICH WAS CONNECTED TO THE UST.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND BEGAN CONTAINMENT AND SPILL PROCEDURES.  APPROX. 50-75 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE/ASPHALT OF THE STATION.  ALL OF THE SPILLED GASOLINE WAS CONTAINED ON THE CONCRETE/ASPHALT PORTION OF THE STATION.  NO GASOLINE EXITED THE STATE PREMISES.  NO GASOLINE ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN OR EARTHEN AREAS AROUND THE STATION.  THE SPILLED GASOLINE WAS COMPLETELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENTS FROM THE TRUCK.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE ABSORPTION (1030 HRS), NO LIQUID REMAINED ON THE CONCRETE/ASPHALT.  THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE PACKAGE OR THE EQUIPMENT.  THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS INATTENTION TO DETAIL ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER.  HE BECAME DISTRACTED WHEN HE ENCOUNTERED THE SPILL DURING HIS INITIAL CONNECTION OF THE HOSE TO THE TRUCK'S DISCHARGE FITTING.  THE DRIVER, AFTER BEING DISTRACTED, DID NOT DOUBLE CHECK TO VERIFY ALL OF HIS PREVIOUSLY SET UP EQUIPMENT WAS READY FOR UNLOADING BEFORE OPENING THE DISCHARGE VALVE.
column169: ALL MID PAC PETROLEUM, LLC DRIVERS WILL BE BRIEFED ON THIS INCIDENT, THE CAUSE AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  EMPHASIS WILL BE PLACED ON THE FOLLOWING:  A). AFTER A DISTRACTION OCCURS, WE NEED TO TAKE A "STEP BACK" AND COMPOSE OURSELVES BEFORE PROCEEDING B).  WE NEED TO DOUBLE CHECK ALL EQUIPMENT THAT WAS PREVIOUSLY SET UP TO ENSURE IT IS STILL PROPERLY CONFIGURED AND SECURED PRIOR TO OPENING OR BREECHING ANY PART OF THE SYSTEM THAT HAS ACCESS TO THE HAZMAT PRODUCT.

column168: Two trucks were involved in an accident, one of which was a Schneider National truck.  Our driver was coming around a curve and the driver & a witness said the other carrier was pulling off of the shoulder back onto the roadway.  He was partially on the roadway with no lights on so our driver ended up colliding with the other carrier.  We were cited originally but that was later recinded.  The resulting collision caused a fire causing our truck and trailer and the other carrier's trailer as a total loss.  The other carrier was hauling resin which caught fire and burned to entirety.  Per the telephonic PHMSA report sent to me it advised that the Schneider truck was hauling 300 pounds of a corrosive material and an undetermined amount of flammable liquid.      There was in fact no corrosive material on board the Schneider trailer.  I confirmed with the shipper (FedEx) and the spill response team that the only thing on our trailer was 90 pounds of cigarette lighters.  Based on the paperwork I believe confusion existed as there was 300 pounds of a material but they were cigars (not sure how someone got corrosive out of that).  Based on the 5800 exceptions each box weighed 45 pounds and total release was less than 5.2 gallons which is why I never filled out the 5800 report form initially.
column169: While we believe this was not our drivers fault the driver will go through remedial training regarding awareness to ensure the driver is demonstrating the right behavriors.  A thorough review of her risk rating tool (internal application monitoring driving habits) was completed as well to ensure there are not other warning signs we needed to take into consideration.

column168: On Tuesday January 12, 2010 a shipment of 162 metric tons of PETN was being unloaded at the port of Morehead City when a forklift operator from SSA Cooper, the stevedoring company, accidentally punctured two (2) fiberboard drums containing PETN. The product is first packaged in a triple layer plastic bag and then stored in fiberboard drums. Approximately 1 gallon of slurry (5 kg of PETN in 25% water) was released from the containers.     Maxam provided advice as to how to manage the situation which included using no metal shovels, no smoking, spray down the product before sweeping it up, contain the area and repack the ruptured drums in another container that will hold water.  The advice appeared to be well received.  Unfortunately, when the Fire Mrshall arrived on the scene, they sprayed the entire container with water, not just the spilled product.    Once the 2 damaged drums were processed, we noticed that additional drums in the container had collapsed as a result of the fire departments attempt to desensitize the PETN with water.  These drums were overpacked before shipment.      In all, 61 fiberboard drums were unacceptable for transportation and were repackaged.  Of these, 48 were due to container suitability issues and 13 were "assumed" to be leaking.  The 13 drums were contaminated with mineral oil and will need to be detroyed.  The other 48 units have been repackaged in approved containers.  All other drums are in good and useable condition.
column169: Maxam has instituted a policy where any spill will require the immediate presence of trained Maxam personnel.  The information provided by Mr. Labelle and Mr. Francelj was correct and if followed would have safely addressed the issue.  We believe that the intital incident, caused by careless handling by the stevedoring employee, was further exacerbated by the subsequent handling practices.  We are happy to provide training whenever we are asked to Emergency Responders, Fire Departments etc. Our goal is zero accidents and incidents, and, if they occur, the safe and efficient handling of such incidents to mitigate damage to the population and the environment.

column168: During offload of inbound flight at San Juan(SJU), the ramp supervisor discovered a piece of checked luggage with a strong smell of Gas.   The supervisor immediately notified our ramp operations agent who proceeded to open the luggage.  Once the luggage was opened, a leaking Propane canister was discovered.  The valve was in the open position when discovered and was immediately turned to off.  The customer was contacted as well as Mr. John Connelly FAA special agent and he interviewed the customer.   Customer advised that he flew from Dallas Love field and he uses the canister for work.  Customers name is INDVIDUAL NOT A COMPANY and after being interviewed by Mr. Connelly he was cleared to go.      The Propane torch cylinder was packed in customers luggage and not declared to airline.  The Propane torch cylinder was screened by TSA but not discovered.
column169: No changes by air carrier but recommend TSA be advised of screening error.

column168: Pittsburg (PIT) Ramp Employees discovered a box leaking battery acid in the aft aircraft bin upon arrival into PIT. The bag was removed and two small streams of acid impacted bin "d" approximately 3/4s of the bin from the bulkhead back. The box was secured, inspected and determined to contain a single automotive spillable battery that appeared to be new (terminals capped). It is unclear if the fluid leaked due to pressure changes or if the battery tipped during transportation or the unloading process.The passenger baggage originated in Fort Meyers (RSW) and flew flight number 3161 to Chicago Midway (MOW) where it transferred to flight number 963 from MOW to PIT. There were no sign of leakage on the first flight segment and inspections of the aircraft supported no leakage on the first leg. Ramp Supervisors immediately contacted Corporate Safety and notified the Captain. Maintenance Control brought a contract mechanic to the aircraft and the Dispatch Department took the aircraft out of service for the remainder of the day as Southwest Mechanics were dispatched to neutralize the spill and perform maintenance inspections.Upon investigation into the shipment, the battery was transported in a propane heater box (propane and/or heater not present) and the Customer Service Agent was informed by the passenger that there was a "regular" battery in the box. No further visual inspection or questioning of the Passenger occurred and the box was accepted as passenger baggage. The spill was reported to the FAA (Special Agent Joe Ballas) and the National Response Center.
column169: Additional Training and individual coaching on existing policy regarding batteries (within company). No external recommendations
